# Nasiko Obsidian Knowledge Base

The `vault/` folder is an Obsidian vault (plain Markdown) co-located with this repo. Use it as the **source of truth for why and how**, while code and `docs/` remain the source of truth for **what runs today**.

## When to use the vault vs code

| Question | Look here first |
|----------|-----------------|
| How does X work right now? | Code, `docs/`, READMEs |
| Why was X built this way? | `vault/decisions/` |
| What are we building next? | `vault/features/` |
| How do subsystems connect? | `vault/architecture/` |
| What changed in a session? | `vault/sessions/` |

In Cursor chat, reference notes with `@vault/...` or `@Codebase` when asking about stored knowledge.

## Vault layout (PARA-inspired, codebase-focused)

```
vault/
  index.md              # Map of the vault — update when adding top-level areas
  architecture/         # System diagrams, service boundaries, data flows
  features/               # Specs, acceptance criteria, open questions (active work)
  decisions/            # ADRs — immutable intent; supersede, don't rewrite history
  reference/            # Stable how-tos (CLI, deploy, env) that complement docs/
  sessions/             # Short session logs (optional daily notes)
  templates/            # Note templates — copy, don't edit in place
```

## Markdown conventions

- Wiki links: `[[note-name]]` (filename without `.md`, kebab-case)
- Link to repo paths inline: `` `app/service/agent_operations_service.py` ``
- Dates in titles or sections: `YYYY-MM-DD`
- Frontmatter on every new note:

```yaml
---
title: Human-readable title
type: architecture | feature | decision | reference | session
status: draft | active | done | superseded
tags: [nasiko, ...]
created: YYYY-MM-DD
updated: YYYY-MM-DD
---
```

- Tag AI-authored notes: `ai/created` on create, `ai/edited` on edit (in `tags` or body)
- Do **not** bold markdown headings (`## Section`, not `## **Section**`)

## Note types

### Feature (`vault/features/`)

- Problem, goals, non-goals
- Affected services/paths (with links)
- Tasks checklist
- Open questions
- On ship: set `status: done` and link to `vault/decisions/` if a significant choice was made

### ADR (`vault/decisions/`)

Name: `NNNN-short-title.md` (next number after highest in folder).

```markdown
## Status
Proposed | Accepted | Superseded by [[other-adr]]

## Context
## Decision
## Consequences
```

Never delete ADRs; mark superseded and link forward.

### Architecture (`vault/architecture/`)

- One concern per note; link related notes with `[[...]]`
- Prefer mermaid for flows; keep diagrams in the note

## Agent workflow (code + vault together)

**Before implementing a non-trivial feature**

1. Read `vault/index.md` and any linked `features/` or `architecture/` notes
2. If none exist, create a draft feature note from `vault/templates/feature.md`

**While implementing**

3. Update the feature note checklist and affected paths
4. Record non-obvious choices in a new ADR when the decision is hard to reverse

**After completing work**

5. Update `updated` in frontmatter; add a one-line entry under `## Log` (new bullet only — never rewrite old log lines):

```markdown
## Log
- 2026-05-16 — 🤖 Implemented agent upload validation; see `app/service/agent_upload_service.py`
```

6. Add `[[wiki-links]]` from architecture or index notes when it improves discoverability

**Queries without clutter**

- Answer from existing notes when asked; do not create notes unless the user asks to document or the task requires a feature/ADR/session record

## Obsidian compatibility

- Files are standard Markdown; avoid HTML-only constructs
- Preserve existing `[[links]]` and frontmatter keys
- Do not modify `.obsidian/` (Cursor ignores it via `.cursorignore`)
- Optional: open `vault/` as the vault root in Obsidian while the repo root stays open in Cursor

## Sensitive content

Never store secrets, tokens, or contents of `.env`, `.nasiko-local.env`, or `superuser_credentials.json` in the vault. Reference env var *names* only.
